cs.SI, cs.NI, cs.DC, cs.SY, cs.CE 

The paper discusses the design of future information systems that are comprised of numerous, heterogeneous, resource-constrained and error-prone components. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI), Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), Systems and Control (cs.SY), or Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE). However, since the paper specifically focuses on the engineering of organic overlay networks with predictable macroscopic properties, it is most likely to belong to the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI).
